04529nam a22007095i 9781501724497DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20181993nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017244977 a10.7591/97815017244972doi  a(DE-B1597)515591  a(OCoLC)1129167196  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR658.B63bP37 1993 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a822/.3093562201 aPaster, Gail Kern, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Body Embarrassed :bDrama and the Disciplines of Shame in Early Modern England /cGail Kern Paster. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b12 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTE ON TEXTS -- tINTRODUCTION. Civilizing the Humoral Body -- t1. LEAKY VESSELS: The Incontinent Women of City Comedy -- t2. LAUDABLE BLOOD: Bleeding, Difference, and Humoral Embarrassment -- t3. COVERING His Ass: The Scatological Imperatives of Comedy -- t4. COMPLYING WITH THE Due: Narratives of Birth and the Reproduction of Shame -- t5. QUARRELING WITH THE DUG, or I AM GLAD You DID NOT NURSE HIM -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMen and women in early modern Europe experienced their bodies very differently from the ways in which contemporary men and women do. In this challenging and innovative book, Gail Kern Pasterexamines representations of the body in Elizabethan-Jacobean drama in the light of humoral medical theory, tracing the connections between the history of the visible social body and the history of the subject's body as experienced from within.Focusing on specific bodily functions and on changes in the forms of embarrassment associated with them, Paster extends the insights of such critics and theorists as Mikhail Bakhtin, Norbert Elias, and Thomas Laqueur. She first surveys comic depictions of incontinent women as "leaky vessels" requiring patriarchal management and then considers the relation between medical bloodletting practices and the gender implications of blood symbolism. Next she relates the practice of purging to the theme of shame and assays ideas about pregnancy, childbirth, and nursing in medical and other nonliterary texts. Paster then turns to the use of reproductive processes in the plot structures of key Shakespeare plays and in Dekker's, Ford's, and Rowley's Witch of Edmonton.Including twelve vivid illustrations, The Body Embarrassed will be fascinating reading for students and scholars in the fields of Renaissance studies, gender studies, literary theory, the history of drama, andcultural history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish dramay17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aHuman body in literature. 0aShame in literature. 4aEngland. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172449740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501724497423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501724497/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK